    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-03-10T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-03-10T09:00:00-05:00" n="415"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d415">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">684A.86/3–1052: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 415<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Lebanon (<persName corresp="#p_MHB1"
                            type="from">Minor</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d415fn1">Repeated to Amman, Baghdad, Cairo, Damascus, Jidda,
                        Paris, London, and Tel Aviv.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Beirut</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-03-10T16:00:00+02:00"
                            >March 10, 1952—4 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>929. Replying <gloss target="#t_Depcirgram1">Depcirgram</gloss> [<hi
                        rend="italic">sic</hi>] 758 March 4. Legation believes discussions on Arab
                    collective security pact, <persName corresp="#p_ZKSM1">Zafrullah</persName>’s
                    recent tour and growing desire for resumption Arab-Israeli trade do open
                    prospects for progress toward peace settlement but at same time we strongly
                    believe these tendencies will not be translated into official action in <gloss
                        target="#t_Leb1">Leb</gloss> before such time as (1) Palestine refugee
                    problem is settled; (2) some solution of Anglo-Egyptian problem is achieved; and
                    (3) there is unmistakable evidence which Arab states can see of a truly unbiased
                    US policy toward Arabs and Israel.</p>
                <p>While <gloss target="#t_Leb1">Leb</gloss> officialdom professes to be groping for
                    some action in direction of peace, it recognizes strong popular feeling of
                    kinship with Egyptian people. Therefore, <gloss target="#t_Leb1">Leb</gloss>
                    Govt cannot be expected to take lead among Arab states nor to take any concrete
                    action toward peace settlement in face of local popular sentiment.</p>
                <p>Lebanese not yet taken official action on Arab collective security pact. Leg has
                    copy of it. We assume this lengthy confidential text is available to Dept and
                    other missions. If desired, we can translate and forward it. Some Lebanese
                    express opinion that strongest factor in progress toward peace is continual
                    decline in US private contributions to Israel.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MHB1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Minor</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
